WEBVTT

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:09.570
PROFESSOR: Welcome back
to recitation.

00:00:09.570 --> 00:00:12.720
In this video I want us to work
on the following problem.

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:14.635
So we're going to assume
little f is

00:00:14.635 --> 00:00:16.400
a continuous function.

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:19.660
And if we know that the integral
from 0 to x of f of t

00:00:19.660 --> 00:00:24.880
dt is equal to x squared
sine pi x, I want us to

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:27.940
find little f of 2.

00:00:27.940 --> 00:00:28.930
So I'm going to give
you a little while

00:00:28.930 --> 00:00:30.080
to work on the problem.

00:00:30.080 --> 00:00:33.470
When you're ready, come back and
we'll take a look at how I

00:00:33.470 --> 00:00:34.720
do the problem.

00:00:43.070 --> 00:00:44.040
Welcome back.

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:47.600
So again, we're working on a
problem where we know that f

00:00:47.600 --> 00:00:48.800
is a continuous function.

00:00:48.800 --> 00:00:51.850
We know that the integral from
0 to x is f of t dt is equal

00:00:51.850 --> 00:00:52.820
to a certain function.

00:00:52.820 --> 00:00:55.500
And we want to find f of 2.

00:00:55.500 --> 00:00:57.710
So what we're going to use,
because we know little f is

00:00:57.710 --> 00:00:59.570
continuous, we can
actually use the

00:00:59.570 --> 00:01:01.520
fundamental theorem of calculus.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:07.770
And we know that d dx of this
whole expression here is

00:01:07.770 --> 00:01:09.950
actually little f of x.

00:01:09.950 --> 00:01:11.960
So let's just remind us--

00:01:11.960 --> 00:01:13.210
I'll write it down formally.

00:01:16.380 --> 00:01:26.570
FTC implies that d dx, the
interval from 0 to x f of t dt

00:01:26.570 --> 00:01:27.186
if equal to f of x.

00:01:27.186 --> 00:01:27.272
Right?

00:01:27.272 --> 00:01:29.960
We know that.

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:36.590
So, we know that d dx of the
right-hand side and d dx of

00:01:36.590 --> 00:01:39.190
the left-hand side
are the same.

00:01:39.190 --> 00:01:41.910
And so we know that if we take
d dx of the right-hand side,

00:01:41.910 --> 00:01:43.040
we'll get little f of x.

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:47.810
Because d dx of the left-hand
side of this equation is

00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:48.680
little f of x.

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:52.430
Do d dx of the right-hand side
is also little f of x.

00:01:52.430 --> 00:01:55.230
So now all we have to do is
apply what we know about

00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:59.090
taking derivatives to
find little f of x.

00:01:59.090 --> 00:02:04.205
Then once we find little f of
x we can evaluate it at f

00:02:04.205 --> 00:02:04.880
equal 2, at 2--sorry--
at x equal 2.

00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:07.210
Sorry about that.

00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:10.550
So let's come over to the right
part of the board and

00:02:10.550 --> 00:02:13.530
we'll find d dx of this
function here.

00:02:21.870 --> 00:02:22.830
So what do we have to use?

00:02:22.830 --> 00:02:25.090
We have to use the product rule
and then we'll have to

00:02:25.090 --> 00:02:28.290
use a little chain rule, a
really simple chain rule in

00:02:28.290 --> 00:02:29.290
the second term.

00:02:29.290 --> 00:02:30.910
I'm going to write it
down below, so we

00:02:30.910 --> 00:02:31.770
have some room here.

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:36.550
So the first term, we
get 2x sine pi x.

00:02:36.550 --> 00:02:38.690
The second term we
get x squared.

00:02:38.690 --> 00:02:41.010
Derivative of sine is cosine.

00:02:41.010 --> 00:02:41.690
pi x.

00:02:41.690 --> 00:02:44.210
And then we have to
pull out a pi.

00:02:44.210 --> 00:02:48.940
Which I'll just put, well I'll
put it here for the moment.

00:02:48.940 --> 00:02:51.980
The pi comes from taking
the derivative of pi x.

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:56.670
And now all we need, this
is then f of x, right?

00:02:56.670 --> 00:02:59.610
So I just will remind
us this is f of x.

00:02:59.610 --> 00:03:02.920
Let me put it right here,
a little f of x.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:06.290
So if I want to find f of 2, all
I have to do is evaluate

00:03:06.290 --> 00:03:09.100
this at x equal 2.

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:11.060
So f of 2 is going to equal--

00:03:11.060 --> 00:03:13.450
2 times 2 is 4--

00:03:13.450 --> 00:03:17.560
sine 2 pi plus 4--

00:03:17.560 --> 00:03:20.050
I'll bring the pi in front--

00:03:20.050 --> 00:03:23.040
4 pi cosine 2 pi.

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:24.610
So what do I get?

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:27.010
Sine 2 pi is 0.

00:03:27.010 --> 00:03:28.970
Cosine 2 pi is 1.

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:32.860
So ultimately, I
just get 4 pi.

00:03:32.860 --> 00:03:35.090
So, hopefully you were able to
solve this problem and get the

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:36.950
same answer.

00:03:36.950 --> 00:03:40.220
Now let me remind you, one
more time what we did.

00:03:40.220 --> 00:03:41.440
Let's come over here.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:44.410
We started with a function that
we knew was continuous.

00:03:44.410 --> 00:03:48.280
We knew the integral from 0 to
x of that function was equal

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:50.610
to a certain function of x.

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:53.621
And we wanted to evaluate this
function at a certain, at a

00:03:53.621 --> 00:03:55.530
certain point.

00:03:55.530 --> 00:03:56.840
So what we exploited was the

00:03:56.840 --> 00:03:59.030
fundamental theorem of calculus.

00:03:59.030 --> 00:04:02.700
And the fundamental theorem of
calculus tells us that d dx,

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:06.010
of the left-hand
side is f of x.

00:04:06.010 --> 00:04:09.460
And so that we can take d dx
of the right-hand side and

00:04:09.460 --> 00:04:11.070
figure out what f of x is.

00:04:11.070 --> 00:04:13.290
And then we just evaluate.

00:04:13.290 --> 00:04:15.240
So I think I'll stop there.